@Max b 
I believe that the air pollution is combustion-related air pollution. 
I disagree with you Max, I think New Hampshire is highly effected by this. The graph shows that more than 50% of the deaths by air pollution in NH is from out-of-state pollution. That is highly concerning.

@Sophia Logan-Barré 
Looking at the first display, South Dakota has a very low amount of air pollution deaths per 10,000 people (at least compared to other states). I think this means that there isn't really a problem with air pollution death in South Dakota and that most of the few cases of air pollution death just happen to be caused by pollution from out of state. With a smaller sample size of air pollution deaths, the state's data is much more susceptible to leaning strongly one way or another. I may be wrong though.
If I am right, it goes to show the importance of having a large enough sample size for your data to mean something.

@Madison M. 
Hi Madison, 
I also wonder why New Hampshire has such a high level of death from pollution because we do not have many populated cities. In fact, we are one of the least populated states in the country. My prediction is our pollutants come from Massachusetts. As you said, I hope society will enforce changes that lower the amount of pollution in the air. This will lower pollution-related deaths in-state, as well as out-of-state.
